  <p>Education facility cleaning is not a simplified version of commercial cleaning. It is a distinct compliance environment. where child safety legislation, state education department guidelines and infection control requirements combine to create obligations that most general commercial cleaning providers are structurally unequipped to meet.</p>

  <h2>What Education Cleaning Involves</h2>
  <p>
    Education cleaning covers routine and periodic cleaning of classrooms, science and computer laboratories, common areas, toilets and amenities, canteens and food preparation areas, sports facilities and change rooms, libraries, administration buildings and staff areas.
  </p>
  <p>
    Services must be coordinated around the school calendar and daily occupation patterns. Holiday period deep cleaning programs are a key scheduled component of most education cleaning contracts. requiring separate workforce deployment, specialist equipment and documented completion evidence.
  </p>

  <CalloutBox heading="What this means for education procurement teams">
    <p>Before evaluating on price, confirm that every proposed staff member holds a current working with children check for the relevant state. Verify that the provider's chemical register complies with education department specifications. Confirm the holiday deep clean program is fully scoped and costed. not an afterthought subject to variation. These are threshold questions, not negotiation points.</p>
  </CalloutBox>

  <h2>Where It Applies</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Primary schools and secondary schools</li>
    <li>Special education facilities</li>
    <li>TAFE campuses and vocational training centres</li>
    <li>Universities and higher education institutions</li>
    <li>Early learning and childcare centres</li>
    <li>Boarding schools and residential education facilities</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Each facility type has distinct requirements around access timing, safeguarding compliance and infection control that shape the service delivery methodology.</p>

  <InlineImage
    src="/images/authority/education-tafe-cleaning-inline.jpg"
    alt="University corridor. education facility cleaning compliance context"
    caption="Education facilities require cleaning programs built around child safety compliance, infection control protocols and scheduling aligned to the school calendar."
  />

  <h2>Risks and Compliance Requirements</h2>
  <p>Key risks in education cleaning include:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Disease transmission in high-density student environments</li>
    <li>Chemical exposure to students through inadequate storage or handling</li>
    <li>Slip hazards from wet floors during occupied periods</li>
    <li>Safeguarding failures from inadequate workforce compliance management</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Working with children checks are mandatory for all staff with unsupervised student access. State education department guidelines govern chemical selection, cleaning standards and infection control protocols across all sites.
  </p>

  <QuoteBlock
    quote="The working with children check requirement alone eliminates many general commercial providers from education work. It is not a paperwork exercise. it is a fundamental safeguarding obligation."
    attribution="CPC Education Portfolio Management"
  />

  <h2>Standards and Expectations</h2>
  <p>Education cleaning must comply with state education department guidelines that specify:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Minimum cleaning frequencies for different facility areas</li>
    <li>Approved chemical specifications and storage requirements</li>
    <li>Infection control procedures including outbreak response protocols</li>
    <li>Working with children check requirements and renewal management</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Holiday deep clean specifications align to education department seasonal programs and must be completed before student and staff return. ISO-certified management systems provide the governance foundation that many education procurement frameworks require.
  </p>

